Extract from a conversation below with Theresa at Rivel on the subject =
of SOC2. I=E2=80=99ll get myself up to speed on what WISPs and TOMs are =
but sounds like we make a similar argument to her to try and avoid it. =
Not sure she is correct on the extent of the personal data that they =
have being equal to ours =E2=80=93 but I get her point that they must =
come quite close in some instances where they have done an internal =
survey.

C=20

=20

We have a lot of personal data =E2=80=93 names, titles, emails, phone =
numbers, companies, etc. of the people we interview, and for clients we =
additionally have encrypted passwords and website usage information. For =
all, we also have survey responses and sometimes temporary audio files. =
So it=E2=80=99s quite similar to the data you have, except that you also =
have birthdays and gender, but none of that is =E2=80=98sensitive =
information=E2=80=99. Article 32 of GDPR only states that the data are =
protected in an =E2=80=98appropriate=E2=80=99 manner given the =
sensitivity of the data (see text below and link). For example, if you =
aren=E2=80=99t processing credit card data, you don=E2=80=99t need to =
have PCI compliance. And the cost of the tech implementation needs to be =
considered as well.  I usually tell clients that as a small company we =
don=E2=80=99t claim ISO compliance or have SOC audits performed, that we =
don=E2=80=99t process any sensitive personal data or credit card info, =
and that we have a full WISP and TOMs suitable to protect the data we do =
process. We=E2=80=99ll verify compliance with any law that applies, but =
the law never requires that we have a SOC 2 audit performed =E2=80=93 =
and for us it would be overkill in terms of data sensitivity and cost. =
It=E2=80=99s usually a negotiation. Some contracts will just say that IF =
we have an audit performed, we will give them the results, but since we =
don=E2=80=99t get one done, I never provide it.

=20

https://gdpr-info.eu/art-32-gdpr/

Taking into account the state of the art, the costs of implementation =
and the nature, scope, context and purposes of processing as well as the =
risk of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of =
natural persons, the controller and the processor shall implement =
appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of =
security appropriate to the risk

=20

